## Transfer Learning Using MobileNetV2 for Classification of Normal (N) and Invasive Carcinoma (I\_C) Samples

#### 1\. Pre-trained CNN Architecture and Transfer Learning Strategy

***Architecture***

The chosen architecture for this task is **MobileNetV2**, a lightweight convolutional neural network designed to be efficient for mobile and embedded vision applications(Sandler et al., 2018).

***MobileNetV2 Structure***

* **Convolutional Layers**

  Uses a series of convolutional layers with batch normalization and activation functions.

* **Depthwise Separable Convolutions**

  This technique divides the convolution process into two parts improving computational efficiency.

* **Linear Bottleneck Layer**

  This layer reduces the number of features followed by a depthwise separable convolution for better performance.

* **Global Average Pooling (GAP)**

  This operation reduces the spatial dimensions of the feature maps and prepares the data for the fully connected output layer.

* **Fully Connected Output Layer**

  The output layer corresponds to the number of classes (in this case, Normal (N) and Invasive Carcinoma (I\_C)).

***Transfer Learning Strategy***

* **Pre-trained Model**  
  I used MobileNetV2 pre-trained on the ImageNet-1000 dataset. This model has already learned useful features such as edges, textures, and shapes, which can be transferred to our task.  
* **Freezing the Base Model**  
  Initially, I froze the weights of the MobileNetV2 base model which allows it to act as a feature extractor. The features learned from ImageNet were retained and firstly used without modification.  
* **Custom Classification Layer**  
  I added a custom dense layer on top of the MobileNetV2 model to adapt it to the binary classification problem of Normal vs. Invasive Carcinoma.  
* **Data Augmentation**  
  To mitigate the risk of overfitting due to the small size of the dataset (690 images for training), data augmentation techniques were applied. These include random rotations and flips to introduce diversity into the dataset and expose the model to different variations of the images.

#### 3\. MobileNetV2 Model Customization

* **Base Model**  
  I used MobileNetV2 as the base model with the ‘`include_top=False’` parameter. This ensures that the model’s final classification layer which is specific to the ImageNet classes is not included and we can add our own customized classification layer.  
    
* **Freezing the Base Model**  
  Initially, the base model layers were frozen so that they would not be updated during training. This way the features learned from ImageNet remained unchanged and were used as a fixed feature extractor.  
* **Global Average Pooling (GAP)**  
  GAP was used to convert the output of the convolutional layers into a 1D vector for each image. The output feature maps initially with a shape of (16, 7, 7, 1280\) were reduced to a 1D vector of length 1280\. This is done by averaging the values of each feature channel across the spatial dimensions (height and width).  
* **Prediction Layer**  
  A fully connected dense prediction layer with 1 neuron and a sigmoid activation function was added to output binary classification results (0 for Normal (N), 1 for Invasive Carcinoma (I\_C)).

#### 4\. Training the Model

* **Compiling the Model**  
  The model was compiled using the **Adam optimizer** with a learning rate of **1e-4**. This optimizer is well-suited for fine-tuning pre-trained models. The **binary crossentropy loss** function was used as it is appropriate for binary classification tasks. The **binary accuracy** metric was used to track the model’s performance.  
* **Training and Validation**  
  The model was trained with the training dataset and validated on the validation dataset. The training and validation losses and accuracies were monitored.  
* **Early Stopping**
